      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "## Chemistry Insight\n\nCitric acid's three pKa values are well-separated, reflecting successive deprotonation of its three carboxyl groups. The central hydroxyl group does not deprotonate under normal aqueous conditions. The relatively low pKa₁ (~2.9) makes citric acid effective as a buffer in the acidic range, while pKa₂ and pKa₃ extend its buffering capacity into the mildly acidic to near-neutral pH range — which is why citrate buffers are widely used in biochemistry and food science. The extensive dataset (48 measurements across varied ionic strengths and temperatures) reflects citric acid's importance as a reference ligand in coordination chemistry and analytical applications.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)*",
